Date: 29 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information Disease Information 29 July 2005 Vol. 18 -
No. 30
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_60.HTM#Sec0>

Bluetongue in Spain
Virus detection in cattle
--------------------
See also: 11 Feb 2005, 4 Feb 2005, 10 Dec 2004, 10 Dec 2004, 3 Dec 2004, 5
Nov 2004, 29 Oct 2004, 22 Oct 2004, 22 Oct 2004, 15 Oct 2004
(Date of previous outbreak of bluetongue in Spain reported to the OIE:
December 2004 [clinical outbreak]).
Immediate notification report
Translation of information received on 22 and 27 Jul 2005 from Dr Arnaldo
Cabello Navarro, Deputy Director General of Animal Health, Ministry of
Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, Madrid:
Report date: 22 Jul 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed infection in
the country.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 21 Jul 2005.
Date of start of the event: 18 Jul 2005.
Clinical disease: no.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
First administrative division (Autonomous Community): Andalusia
Lower administrative division (province): Huelva
Type of epidemiological unit: ...
Name of the location: Encinasola
Species: bov
Number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
121 / 47* / 0 / 0 / 0
* without clinical signs
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Central Veterinary Laboratory, Algete
Species examined: bov
Diagnostic tests used: RT-PCR(1)
Date: 21 Jul 2005
Results: positive
Origin of infection: unknown.
Control measures: control of arthropods and other measures in accordance
with Directive 2000/75/EC of the Council of the European Union, dated 20
Nov 2000, laying down specific provisions for the control and eradication
of bluetongue.
Treatment of affected animals: no.
Vaccination prohibited: no; vaccination requires an authorisation issued by
the official Veterinary Services.
Other details/comments: the outbreak was reported within the restriction
zone set up following the epizootics of 2004. Sheep in this zone were
vaccina ted in winter 2004-2005 (i.e. in the absence of vectors) using a
live virus vaccine.
(1) RT-PCR: reverse transcriptase - polymerase chain reaction
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This notice gives additional information indicating that there has been no
clinical disease yet. So far only cattle have been affected. However, we
still don't know the virus type yet. 2004's outbreak involved BT 4
virus. - Mod.PC]
